---
// THE site — the pull infomercial, one continuous motion (Turbo Pump grammar).
// Promoted from /b to / on 2026-07-16 (director ruling); the Structure C spine
// and its components were removed the same day — they survive in git history
// and in docs/gtm/2026-07-12-pull-driven-sales/site-strategy-2026-07-15.md.
// Format and layout are ruled; copy awaits a section-by-section hand-rewrite.
// Round 5 (2026-07-16, director rulings): one cold open only — the old enemy
// story and pain cave merged into THE LINEUP: the suspects for why a skill goes
// from appearing-to-work to appearing-to-fail, managed to reality and grouped
// into six scannable families. Machine reveal: "One machine. The whole lineup."
// Hand-rewrite pass (2026-07-16, director): the PULL and the LINEUP re-voiced —
// pull now names the skill as culprit; the lineup dropped its "how you'd know
// today" column and the "that's the cave" kicker for a lighter, faster read
// (suspects are a clean grouped list; kicker lands on "more than one at a time").
// Round 6 (2026-07-18, director): infomercial arc restored. The page had
// drifted into reading like an eval suite; re-cut to the model's four beats —
// pain (you made it; not your fault, still your problem, a slog you might not
// win) → hard cut to the built world (the LAYER STACK replaces the storyboard)
// → quick how (bring your most important prompt, not the problem child) →
// fan-out wonders. New angle: demonstrated evidence — the card travels
// (org/community), so a break in the wild never reads as "you weren't
// thorough". Feeling: bend-don't-break, swiftly rebuildable. "Case-closing
// machine" retired; fixing demoted to one wonder. Cut in this pass (reinstate
// from git if wanted): the champion sentence + its Claude-models footnote.
// Round 7 (2026-07-18, director): kicker re-voiced verbatim; the cut beat
// re-headlined "Embrace Your Inner Maker." The hero beat rebuilt per the Rob
// Snyder Part-3 grammar ("Watch: just secure the clip and switch it on") —
// heavy visual, low exposition: pull up the rock-solid skill (the card), tell
// the agent to run down the suspects (a terminal exchange), win. The 01-03
// steps grid and the razor/travel paragraphs were compressed to single lines.
// Round 8 (2026-07-18, director): three panels collapsed to the ruled two-beat
// supply. Beat A = V3 ("case file, not a mystery") + the terminal, re-scripted
// so the READER is the hero — the AI investigates and administrates, they
// judge and craft the clinching eval. Strictly reactive: no telemetry, nothing
// caught in advance. Beat B = "Embrace Your Inner Maker." + the layer stack
// (mechanism named, not explained). The card moved to the fan-out as the
// evidence-that-travels prop. "Weird Tuesday" purged site-wide.
// Round 9 (2026-07-18, director): the terminal exchange retired (in git) —
// Beat A's visual is now the card itself: "Meet the case file." shows the
// case file. Not the solution in action, but the world where it's handled.
// The fan-out keeps the travels kicker as text; the image lives up top only.
// Round 11 (2026-07-18, director): fan-out rebuilt as OFFENSE — Rob's beat is
// a torrent of other instances, so three doors that each contain a multitude:
// the whole repo (bulk adopt), the growth program (better/cheaper/provable),
// the open door (receiving dock: testimony until re-proven; ships with the
// case file). Six ask/answer tiles + standalone travels kicker retired to git.
// Amended same day: defense/offense sub deleted (defense framing again);
// door 3 re-ruled as the RECEIVING DOCK — a checkpoint, not an open door:
// arrivals re-verified, screened for malice, field lessons become tests.
// Also: Ship cell gets the accent border; "bend instead of break" cut from
// Beat B (honesty ruling: they DO break — that's the point; they rebuild).
// Round 10 (2026-07-18, director): Beat B's visual is now the BUILD FLOW —
// the chronological make pipeline (Frame → Research → Draft → Proof →
// Measure → gate → Ship) from the data model / Authority→Evidence explainer,
// shown as an assembly line with the gate as a visible checkpoint. The layer
// stack retired to git. Minimal words: stage + artifact, one solidity line.
// Copy rationale: docs/gtm/2026-07-12-pull-driven-sales/voc-language-research-2026-07-16.md
//                 docs/gtm/2026-07-12-pull-driven-sales/competitor-landscape-2026-07-16.md
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";
import "../styles/global.css";

const repoUrl = "https://github.com/sociotechnica-org/skillmaker-studio";
const issuesUrl = "https://github.com/sociotechnica-org/skillmaker-studio/issues";
const installLines = [
  "curl -fsSL https://skillmaker.studio/install.sh | sh",
  "skillmaker adopt",
];

const title = "Skillmaker Studio — Your agent did something weird again.";
const description =
  "You made a skill and the world keeps changing under it. Skillmaker Studio builds skills in layers — research, design, proof, history — so they bend instead of break, rebuild fast, and carry their evidence wherever they go.";

// The suspects, flattened to a scannable checklist (categories dropped per
// director ruling: an index card reads faster than six labeled groups).
const suspects = [
  "The model changed under it.",
  "The model got quietly nerfed.",
  "It ran on a model it was never rated for.",
  "The agent runtime updated.",
  "A skill up- or downstream changed its handoff.",
  "The general prompt shifted around it.",
  "New skills crowded out its context.",
  "A teammate “improved” it — or you forked it.",
  "It was never sharp: too vague, too broad, too long.",
  "Nothing. A 1-in-1,000 fluke.",
];

// The build flow — the make pipeline as an assembly line, stage names from
// the data model (Frame → Research → Draft → Proof → Measure → gate → Ship).
// Each caption is only the artifact the stage leaves behind.
const flow = [
  {
    num: "01",
    name: "Frame",
    desc: "The job, the boundaries, what counts as done.",
  },
  {
    num: "02",
    name: "Research",
    desc: "Evidence in; failure modes named.",
  },
  {
    num: "03",
    name: "Draft",
    desc: "A design with reasons — the design writes the SKILL.md.",
  },
  {
    num: "04",
    name: "Proof",
    desc: "What “good” means, as tests anyone can run.",
  },
  {
    num: "05",
    name: "Measure",
    desc: "Pass rate × confidence, pinned to version × model.",
  },
  {
    gate: true,
    name: "Gate",
    desc: "The numbers hold, or it doesn't ship.",
  },
  {
    num: "06",
    name: "Ship",
    desc: "Receipts frozen; everyone downstream flagged.",
  },
];

const wild = [
  {
    quote: "AI is not a tool, it's a tiny Kafkaesque bureaucracy inside of your codebase.",
    source: "Hacker News",
    url: "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=43683012",
  },
  {
    quote:
      "Application prompts overfit the model they are using… Switch model, the prompt no longer produces the output you expect.",
    source: "Hacker News",
    url: "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48868086",
  },
  {
    quote:
      "I keep it adhoc - models change so frequently that prompts are always broken all the time.",
    source: "Ask HN",
    url: "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42325485",
  },
];

// The fan-out — three doors into the offense, each holding a multitude
// (Rob's beat is a torrent of other instances). VoC quote as the title,
// industry terms in the body.
const doors = [
  {
    label: "the whole repo",
    quote: "“Do this for all 89.”",
    body: "Bulk-adopt the company repo in place — zero files moved. Every skill gets the same foundation and its own case file, and the whole portfolio lands on one board: gaps visible, receipts attached, dead weight obvious.",
  },
  {
    label: "the growth program",
    quote: "“Same output, half the tokens.”",
    body: "Every skill carries its own improvement loop. Fork it to a cheaper model and race it on the same fixtures. Tighten it and prove nothing regressed. New model drops? Re-run the proof and cash it in the same week.",
  },
  {
    label: "the receiving dock",
    quote: "“Who knows where it's been.”",
    body: "Nothing walks straight in. Every arriving skill — a teammate's fork, a community find, your own back from the wild — hits the dock first: re-verified against its proof, screened for anything malicious, its field lessons folded back in as new tests.",
  },
];

const objections = [
  {
    q: "“Isn't this just an eval suite?”",
    a: "Eval suites point at your outputs and hand back a number — they never hold your skill. Skillmaker does: design, proof, versions, receipts, lineage — one git-native bundle that ships with its evidence. Scoring is one thing it does, not the thing it is.",
  },
  {
    q: "“Isn't this slower than just shipping it?”",
    a: "Up front? Yes — writing down what good means takes real time. But you pay the hours either way: once here, on purpose, with a receipt — or every incident, in the dark.",
  },
  {
    q: "“Do we have to restructure our repo?”",
    a: "No. adopt works in place — 59/60 and 39/39 skills adopted cleanly on real public repos. Zero files moved.",
  },
  {
    q: "“Where does my data go?”",
    a: "Nowhere. Free, local, MIT-licensed, no account. It phones nothing home.",
  },
  {
    q: "“And when you get acquired?”",
    a: "Your receipts are plain files in your git history. If we vanished tomorrow, your evidence wouldn't. No account, no cloud, nothing to sunset.",
  },
  {
    q: "“I'm not an evals person.”",
    a: "You don't need to be. If your current process is a vibe check, that's a real start — our agents help you write it down in plain English and make it repeatable. You judge; they build.",
  },
];
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
    <title>{title}</title>
    <meta name="description" content={description} />
    <meta property="og:title" content={title} />
    <meta property="og:description" content={description} />
    <meta property="og:type" content="website" />
    <meta name="twitter:card" content="summary" />
    <link rel="icon" href="data:," />
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com" />
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin />
    <link
      href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Special+Elite&family=Source+Serif+4:ital,opsz,wght@0,8..60,400;0,8..60,600;1,8..60,400&display=swap"
      rel="stylesheet"
    />
  </head>
  <body class="min-h-screen bg-canvas text-ink antialiased">
    <Header />
    <main>
      <!-- THE PULL — the only cold open -->
      <section class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 pb-14 pt-16 sm:pt-24">
        <h1 class="max-w-3xl text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.1] tracking-tight text-ink sm:text-5xl">
          Your agent did something weird again.
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-ink-dim">
          No crash. No error on a dashboard. Just <em>confidently wrong</em>, in
          front of someone who matters. A skill you made is to blame. And you
          can&#39;t say for sure why.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- THE LINEUP — the suspects as an old-school index-card checklist -->
      <section class="border-y border-border bg-canvas">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-14">
          <h2 class="max-w-3xl text-2xl font-semibold leading-snug tracking-tight text-ink sm:text-3xl">
            Meet the suspects.
          </h2>

          <div class="mt-8 max-w-3xl">
            <div
              class="rounded-md border border-ink/40 bg-surface px-6 pb-4 pt-4 sm:px-8"
              style="box-shadow: 5px 5px 0 var(--color-paper-dark); transform: rotate(-0.5deg);"
            >
              <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between border-b-2 pb-2" style="border-color: #c15c3f;">
                <span class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-widest text-ink-dim">Root cause</span>
                <span class="font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest text-ink-dim">check all that apply</span>
              </div>
              <div class="grid gap-x-10 sm:grid-cols-2">
                <ul>
                  {suspects.slice(0, 5).map((s) => (
                    <li class="flex items-start gap-3 border-b border-border py-2.5">
                      <span class="mt-0.5 inline-block h-4 w-4 shrink-0 rounded-sm border border-ink/50 bg-canvas"></span>
                      <span class="text-[15px] leading-snug text-ink">{s}</span>
                    </li>
                  ))}
                </ul>
                <ul>
                  {suspects.slice(5).map((s) => (
                    <li class="flex items-start gap-3 border-b border-border py-2.5">
                      <span class="mt-0.5 inline-block h-4 w-4 shrink-0 rounded-sm border border-ink/50 bg-canvas"></span>
                      <span class="text-[15px] leading-snug text-ink">{s}</span>
                    </li>
                  ))}
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p class="mt-10 max-w-3xl font-medium leading-relaxed text-ink">
            Probably not your fault. Entirely your problem. And running it down
            means a long slog that can still end at &ldquo;not sure.&rdquo;
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- BEAT A — supply that fits PULL (V3, director-ruled): the case file,
           not the mystery. The reader is the hero: the AI investigates and
           administrates; they judge and craft the clinching eval. Strictly
           reactive — no telemetry, nothing "caught in advance". -->
      <section class="border-y border-border bg-surface">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-14">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink sm:text-3xl">
            Meet the case file.
          </h2>
          <p class="mt-4 max-w-2xl leading-relaxed text-ink-dim">
            A skill made in Skillmaker never hands you a mystery — it hands you
            a case file: every suspect checked, evidence attached, likeliest
            first. You supply the judgment — the call, the clinching eval —
            and the Studio runs everything else, receipts included.
          </p>

          <div class="mt-8 max-w-3xl">
            <img
              src="/skill-card.png"
              width="2012"
              height="1542"
              loading="lazy"
              decoding="async"
              alt="A Skillmaker skill card for william-draft-skill-md — a dossier with a risk heat map across the world, its neighborhood, the job, the people, the skill, and luck; 92% pass on Opus, in sync at v0.3, output flagged as the untested blind spot."
              class="w-full"
            />
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- BEAT B — the strong supply follow-up: the build system itself
           (Rob's Part-4 mechanism — named, not explained). -->
      <section class="border-y border-border bg-canvas">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-14">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink sm:text-3xl">
            Embrace Your Inner Maker.
          </h2>
          <p class="mt-4 max-w-2xl leading-relaxed text-ink-dim">
            Skillmaker Studio is a build system for skills: research, design,
            and proof under every prompt, versioned in your git. Skills built
            this way rebuild in hours when the world moves.
          </p>

          <div class="mt-8 grid max-w-3xl gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
            {
              flow.map((f) => (
                <div
                  class={
                    f.name === "Ship"
                      ? "rounded-md border-2 border-accent bg-surface px-6 py-6 sm:col-span-2"
                      : f.gate
                        ? "rounded-md border-2 border-dashed border-accent-dim bg-canvas px-5 py-4"
                        : "rounded-md border border-ink/40 bg-surface px-5 py-4"
                  }
                >
                  {f.num ? (
                    <span class="font-mono text-[10px] text-accent">{f.num}</span>
                  ) : (
                    <span class="font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest text-accent-dim">■</span>
                  )}
                  <p class="mt-1 font-mono text-sm uppercase tracking-wide text-ink">{f.name}</p>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-xs leading-relaxed text-ink-dim">{f.desc}</p>
                </div>
              ))
            }
          </div>

          <p class="mt-8 max-w-3xl font-medium leading-relaxed text-ink">
            Every stage leaves its artifact in your git. When the world moves,
            you don&#39;t start at zero — you re-enter at the stage that
            slipped.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- THE FAN-OUT — but wait, there's more: the asks in your DMs,
           answered from inside the built world. -->
      <section class="border-y border-border bg-surface">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-14">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink sm:text-3xl">
            And that&#39;s just the first skill.
          </h2>
          <div class="mt-8 grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-3">
            {
              doors.map((d) => (
                <div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-canvas p-6">
                  <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-widest text-accent">{d.label}</p>
                  <p class="mt-3 font-semibold text-ink">{d.quote}</p>
                  <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-dim">{d.body}</p>
                </div>
              ))
            }
          </div>
          <p class="mt-8 max-w-3xl font-medium leading-relaxed text-ink">
            Every ask still carries the silent suffix: “…and don&#39;t break
            it.” Here that isn&#39;t a promise on vibes — it&#39;s the proof,
            re-run.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- THE SECRET -->
      <section class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-14">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink sm:text-3xl">
          The secret is the trail.
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl leading-relaxed text-ink-dim">
          Every number is pinned to the exact skill version and model that earned
          it. Every design choice is linked to the evidence behind it. So when a
          skill is stable but wrong — running clean, doing the job badly — you can
          see it, trace it, and fix the process, not just the prompt. And the
          culprit question — model, skill, teammate, you — becomes a lookup,
          not a fight.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl font-medium leading-relaxed text-ink">
          Drift doesn&#39;t stop. It stops mattering.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- THE WILD — verified public quotes -->
      <section class="border-y border-border bg-surface">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-14">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink sm:text-3xl">
            You&#39;ve already said it.
          </h2>
          <div class="mt-8 grid gap-6 sm:grid-cols-3">
            {
              wild.map((w) => (
                <figure class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-canvas p-6">
                  <blockquote class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink">“{w.quote}”</blockquote>
                  <figcaption class="mt-3">
                    <a
                      href={w.url}
                      class="font-mono text-xs text-accent transition hover:text-accent-dim"
                      rel="noreferrer"
                    >
                      — {w.source} &rarr;
                    </a>
                  </figcaption>
                </figure>
              ))
            }
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- OBJECTIONS -->
      <section class="border-y border-border bg-surface">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-14">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink sm:text-3xl">
            Our Favorite Objections.
          </h2>
          <div class="mt-8 grid gap-6 sm:grid-cols-2">
            {
              objections.map((o) => (
                <div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-canvas p-6">
                  <h3 class="font-semibold text-ink">{o.q}</h3>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-dim">{o.a}</p>
                </div>
              ))
            }
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ACT -->
      <section class="border-t border-border bg-surface">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-16">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink sm:text-3xl">Find out fast.</h2>

          <div class="mt-8 max-w-3xl rounded-lg border border-border bg-canvas shadow-2xl shadow-black/40">
            <div class="flex items-center justify-between border-b border-border px-4 py-3">
              <div class="flex items-center gap-1.5" aria-hidden="true">
                <span class="h-2.5 w-2.5 rounded-full bg-ink/15"></span>
                <span class="h-2.5 w-2.5 rounded-full bg-ink/15"></span>
                <span class="h-2.5 w-2.5 rounded-full bg-ink/15"></span>
              </div>
              <span class="font-mono text-xs text-ink-dim">ninety seconds</span>
              <span></span>
            </div>
            <pre class="overflow-x-auto px-4 py-4 font-mono text-[13px] leading-relaxed text-ink">{installLines.map((line) => `$ ${line}`).join("\n")}</pre>
            <p class="border-t border-border px-4 py-3 text-xs text-ink-dim">
              Free. Local. MIT. Phones nothing home. On the repo you already have.
            </p>
          </div>

          <p class="mt-8 max-w-2xl text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-dim">
            Want hands-on help? We&#39;re working with a small first round of design
            partners —
            <a href={issuesUrl} class="text-accent transition hover:text-accent-dim" rel="noreferrer">open an issue</a>
            and tell us what broke. Running skills as a team?
            <a href={issuesUrl} class="text-accent transition hover:text-accent-dim" rel="noreferrer">Talk to us</a>
            — we&#39;re designing the multi-player studio with a handful of companies.
          </p>

          <div class="mt-12 max-w-3xl border-t border-border pt-10">
            <p class="leading-relaxed text-ink-dim">
              We can&#39;t make your agent predictable — nobody can; that&#39;s what
              you hired it for. We can make sure nothing drifts silently, nothing
              fails anonymously, and nothing stays wrong. And the next time it goes
              weird, you won&#39;t sit there wondering if you&#39;re crazy. You&#39;ll
              look it up.
            </p>
            <p class="mt-4 text-lg font-medium text-ink">The only thing you risk is finding out.</p>
            <p class="mt-8">
              <a href={repoUrl} class="text-sm font-medium text-accent transition hover:text-accent-dim" rel="noreferrer">
                View on GitHub &rarr;
              </a>
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
